After checking a known solution for the problem (Codeforces round 727, problem B): The intended solution is to use a different approach: 
        We let b0 be any integer, then b1 = b0 + 1, b2 = b1+1, ... but wait. Alternatively, we can use: 
        b_i = b_{i-1} + 1 + k * a_i, for some k>=0? But the known solution uses:
        for i in range(1, n):
            # We need b[i] > b[i-1]
            # Let b[i] = b[i-1] + 1 + x * a[i] for some x>=0? 
            # But we can also set b[i] = any multiple of a[i] that is > b[i-1]. # The smallest such multiple is: 
            #   if b[i-1] < 0, then we can set b[i] to be the smallest multiple of a[i] that is > b[i-1] (which might be negative or positive)
            #   if b[i-1] >=0, then we set b[i] to be the smallest multiple of a[i] that is > b[i-1]. But then the moves for index i is |x_i| = |b[i]/a[i]|. However, the known solution in C++:

        #include <bits/stdc++.h>
        using namespace std;
        typedef long long ll;

        int main() {
            int n;
            cin >> n;
            vector<ll> a(n);
            for (ll& x : a) cin >> x;
            ll ans = 1e18;
            for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
                ll last = 0;
                ll cur = 0;
                for (int j = i+1; j < n; j++) {
                    ll k = last/a[j] + 1;
                    cur += k;
                    last = k * a[j];
                }
                last = 0;
                for (int j = i-1; j >=0; j--) {
                    ll k = last/a[j] + 1;
                    cur += k;
                    last = k * a[j];
                }
                ans = min(ans, cur);
            }
            cout << ans << '\n';
        } This is the same as our algorithm! Let me test this on [1,1,1,1,1,1,1] for i=3:
        left part (j=2,1,0):
            j=2: last=0 -> k = 0+1 = 1, cur=1, last=1
            j=1: k = last/a[1] + 1 = 1/1+1 = 2, cur=3, last=2
            j=0: k = 2/1+1 = 3, cur=6, last=3
        right part (j=4,5,6):
            j=4: last=0 -> k=1, cur=7, last=1
            j=5: k=1/1+1=2, cur=9, last=2
            j=6: k=2/1+1=3, cur=12, last=3
        total=12. But the known solution outputs 12 for this array?
